Dewey’s lectures on social philosophy in LC suggest several ways in which resources from the social sciences may be employed to derive immanent standards for social criticism. In fact, consistent with Kadlec’s general contention that Dewey’s “philosophy of the social” is concerned with social conditions for growth, Dewey, in LC, considers conditions for the development of individual capacities that enable social and political participation. Such conditions are specified in terms of social relationships in and between groups, and embodied in social practices and institutions. A conception of immanent standards thus arises with a certain degree of sociological specificity: positive conditions for individual development are analyzed in terms of relationships that contribute “to free intercourse, to unhampered exchange of ideas, to mutual respect and friendship and love” (LC: 90). Negatively, practices and institutions are to be criticized to the extent that they embody relationships of domination disabling individual development and social and political participation. In fact, Dewey’s social philosophy confronts the issue of domination and power on a broad scale: in line with Rogers’ interpretation of Dewey’s ethical and political writings, it is concerned with ways in which political power is exercised arbitrarily in modern democracies (2009: 213–24); but it also, and consistent with Hildreth’s interpretation (2009: 791–4), shows sensitivity to how power relations are embedded in customs in the civil and private sphere. Dewey seeks, in LC, to establish an ideal typical conception of domination meant to capture “any system of relationship which effectively places one person in subjugation to another – children subjects to their parents, wives to their husbands, subjects to their rulers, laborers to their employers” (LC: 92). As Hildreth has pointed out on the basis of other textual sources (2009: 793), there are parallels between Dewey’s approach to power and Steven Lukes’s ‘third dimension of power’;
7
 in LC, Dewey aims to capture the more inconspicuous aspects of power that shape agents’ attitudes and views of themselves: he thus accounts for “servility, ignorance … and obsequiousness” in terms of “a system which forces men into subservience’ (LC: 96) and he particularly mentions the ways in which most Western women until recent times have accepted their inferiority ‘as an established fact” (LC: 77).
